                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12740797" author="gsingers" created="Sat, 8 Aug 2009 01:41:40 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;How is this different from normalize(power) that is already on Vector?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12740821" author="dlwh" created="Sat, 8 Aug 2009 03:09:25 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;normalize(power) returns this.divide(norm(power)).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;norm(p) == ||v||_p,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;normalize(p) == v / ||v||_p&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;norm(p) is useful to check if a vector is sufficiently close to 0, e.g. if the difference between two phases of an optimization is close enough to convergence.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
